  --set crds.enabled=true
3. Create a ClusterIssuer:
yamlapiVersion: cert-manager.io/v1
kind: ClusterIssuer
metadata:
  name: letsencrypt-prod
spec:
  acme:
    server: https://acme-v02.api.letsencrypt.org/directory
    email: your-email@example.com
    privateKeySecretRef:
      name: letsencrypt-prod-key
    solvers:
    - http01:
        gatewayHTTPRoute:
          parentRefs:
          - name: public-gateway
            namespace: nginx-gateway
bashkubectl apply -f cluster-issuer.yaml
4. Request the certificate:
yamlapiVersion: cert-manager.io/v1
kind: Certificate
metadata:
  name: web-app-tls
  namespace: nginx-gateway
spec:
  secretName: web-app-tls
  dnsNames:
  - app.yourdomain.com
  issuerRef:
    name: letsencrypt-prod
    kind: ClusterIssuer
bashkubectl apply -f certificate.yaml
kubectl get certificate -n nginx-gateway -w
Wait for READY: True. Check kubectl describe certificate web-app-tls -n nginx-gateway if it hangs — usually a DNS or port-80-reachability issue.


Path B — No domain yet, or internal/testing use (self-signed cert)
bashopenssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
  -keyout tls.key -out tls.crt \
  -subj "/CN=103.232.25.197"

kubectl create secret tls web-app-tls \
  --cert=tls.crt --key=tls.key \
  -n nginx-gateway
Browsers will show a security warning (expected/normal for self-signed) — fine for internal testing, not for production public use.

Steps common to both — add the HTTPS listener and update the route
5. Add an HTTPS listener to the Gateway:
yamlapiVersion: gateway.networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Gateway
metadata:
  name: public-gateway
  namespace: nginx-gateway
spec:
  gatewayClassName: nginx
  listeners:
  - name: http
    protocol: HTTP
    port: 80
    allowedRoutes:
      namespaces:
        from: All
  - name: https
    protocol: HTTPS
    port: 443
    tls:
      mode: Terminate
      certificateRefs:
      - name: web-app-tls
        kind: Secret
    allowedRoutes:
      namespaces:
        from: All
# kubectl apply -f gateway.yaml

6. Attach your HTTPRoute to the new https listener too (keep http as well for now, or redirect it — see below):
yamlapiVersion: gateway.networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: HTTPRoute
metadata:
  name: web-app-route
  namespace: web
spec:
  parentRefs:
  - name: public-gateway
    namespace: nginx-gateway
    sectionName: http
  - name: public-gateway
    namespace: nginx-gateway
    sectionName: https
  rules:
  - backendRefs:
    - name: web-app-svc
      port: 80

# kubectl apply -f web-app-route.yaml

7. Verify and test:
bashkubectl get gateway public-gateway -n nginx-gateway -o yaml   # confirm https listener Programmed: True
kubectl get svc -n nginx-gateway                              # confirm port 443 now listed
curl -kv https://103.232.25.197/                               # -k skips cert validation if self-signed
Optional — force HTTP to redirect to HTTPS
Once HTTPS works, add a redirect filter so plain http:// visitors get bounced automatically:
yamlapiVersion: gateway.networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: HTTPRoute
metadata:
  name: http-to-https-redirect
  namespace: web
spec:
  parentRefs:
  - name: public-gateway
    namespace: nginx-gateway
    sectionName: http
  rules:
  - filters:
    - type: RequestRedirect
      requestRedirect:
        scheme: https
        statusCode: 301
# bashkubectl apply -f redirect.yaml
